label.value: negative regulation of termination of RNA polymerase II transcription

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of termination of RNA polymerase II transcription.

A cellular process that results in the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a tight junction. A tight junction seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a tight junction. A tight junction seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other.
Any process involved in the dehiscence of an anther to release the pollen grains contained within it.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of anther dehiscence.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of anther dehiscence.

The respiratory system process driven by motile cilia on epithelial cells of the respiratory tract by which mucus and associated inhaled particles and pathogens trapped within it are moved out of the airways.

label.value: positive regulation of imaginal disc-derived wing size

value.value: Any process that increases the size of an imaginal disc-derived wing.
The outer segment of a vertebrate cone photoreceptor that contains membrane discs that are contiguous with the ciliary membrane and containing opsin photoreceptor proteins.
The outer segment of a vertebrate rod photoreceptor that contains sealed membrane discs that are not connected to the ciliary membrane and containing rhodopsin photoreceptor proteins.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a cone photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of opsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. Cone disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane during the development of the cone outer segment and remain contiguous with the ciliary membrane.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a rod photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of rhodopsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. It is thought that rod disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane near the base of the outer segment, which then become completely separated from the ciliary membrane, during the development of the rod outer segment.
The volume enclosed by the membrane of a rod photoreceptor cell disc membrane.
Catalysis of the reaction: methylcytosine + L-ascorbate + O2 = 5-glyceryl-methylcytosine + glyoxylate + CO2.

The proximal region of the photoreceptor connecting cilium is similar to the transition zone of unspecialized primary cilia and houses several major transition zone complexes, including NPHP, MKS, and RPGR.

The distal region of the photoreceptor connecting cilium is structurally unique to the photoreceptor and is maintained by retina-specific protein, SPATA7, and its interacting partners RPGR and RPGRIP1. It is essential for photoreceptor sensory cilium stability.
The process of selecting and or marking the position where endocytosis will occur.
Telodendria are projections that originate from the axon pedicle and form gap junctions with other neurons.
Cone telodendria are projections that originate from the cone pedicle and form gap junctions with other photoreceptors within the outer plexiform layer of the retina.
Rod telodendria are projections that originate from the rod pedicle and form gap junctions with other photoreceptors within the outer plexiform layer of the retina.
Fusion of the membrane of proacrosomal vesicle with the membrane of another proacrosomal vesicle to form the acrosome.
A centrosome-based structure consisting of two cylindrical microtubule-based centrioles and associated components which anchors the flagellum to the sperm head.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of histidine biosynthetic process.

label.value: negative regulation of histidine biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of histidine biosynthetic process.

label.value: positive regulation of histidine biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of histidine biosynthetic process.

A cartilage extracellular matrix complex that mediates interactions between major components of the extracellular matrix such as collagens and proteoglycans and contributes to their fibrillar network. Exists as an obligate homotrimer.

A bacterial type IIA topoisomerase that is unique in its function of introducing negative supercoils into DNA at the expense of ATP hydrolysis and is also capable of relaxing positive supercoils, an activity shared with topoisomerase IV. Typically, it is composed of two copies each of an A subunit (GyrA) and a B subunit (GyrB).

label.value: host interaction involved in quorum sensing

value.value: A quorum sensing process that is modulated by some interaction with a host cell or organism.

The region of a polarized cell that is just below the apical region. For example, in a polarized epithelial cell, the apical region has an exposed surface and lies opposite to the basal lamina that separates the epithelium from other tissue so the subapical region is further from the exposed surface and closer to the basal lamina.
The region in the apical portion of multiciliated epithelial cells where the ciliary basal bodies cluster.

label.value: maintenance of ciliary planar beating movement pattern

value.value: Any process involved in maintaining the planar beating pattern of ciliary movement pattern. Connection between the outer doublets and the central pair via the radial spokes constrains ciliary movement to the planar beating pattern. Cilia that lack this connection, such as those in the embryonic node or Kupfer's vesicle, display radial movement.

definition.value: Note that we deem cilium and microtubule-based flagellum to be equivalent.

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of blastocyst development.

The process in which the larynx is generated and organized. The larynx is a continuation of the pharynx that is involved in breathing, sound production, and protecting the trachea against food aspiration.

The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a larynx from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the larynx and ends with the mature structure. A larynx is a continuation of the pharynx that is involved in breathing, sound production, and protecting the trachea against food aspiration.
Binding to coenzyme A, 3'-phosphoadenosine-(5')diphospho(4')pantatheine, an acyl carrier in many acylation and acyl-transfer reactions in which the intermediate is a thiol ester.
Binding to succinyl-CoA, an omega-carboxyacyl-CoA having succinoyl as the S-acyl component.
Binding to an acyl-CoA, a thioester that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid.
A complex which stabilizes the binding of and correctly positions the outer dynein arm complex along an A-tubule of the flagellar axoneme outer doublet microtubules.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a motile cilium.
Binds to and increases the activity of a recombinase.
A protein complex that binds to a recombinase and incrseases its activity.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in prenyl-FMNH2, an essential cofactor for the decarboxylase enzymes UbiD and Fdc1.
Binding to prenyl-FMNH2, a flavin mononucleotide obtained by prenylation of the N-10 position of FMNH2 followed by cyclisation. An essential cofactor for the decarboxylase enzymes UbiD and Fdc1.
A glycocalyx on the the endolymphatic surface of a cochlear hair cell that coats the external surface of each stereocilium and maintains a small distance between adjacent stereocilia in the bundle.

label.value: regulation of post-translational protein targeting to membrane, translocation

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of posttranslational protein translocation through the ER membrane.

label.value: negative regulation of post-translational protein targeting to membrane, translocation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of posttranslational protein translocation through the ER membrane.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a terminal acetylenic compound, a compound which contains a terminal alkyne moiety in which a carbon of the carbon-carbon triple bond (aka C#C) moiety is attached to a hydrogen atom.
The carbohydrate rich layer at the outermost periphery of a sperm cell.

The carbohydrate-rich layer lining the vascular endothelium connected to the endothelium through a variety of molecules, mainly proteoglycans and glycoproteins. These form a network in which soluble molecules, either plasma- or endothelium-derived, are incorporated.
The carbohydrate rich layer at the outermost periphery of a platelet.
